Effects: Exercises the liver, controls bile, relieves a painful coccyx.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤¸à¤¿à¤‚à¤¹à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Simha (à¤¸à¤¿à¤‚à¤¹) - lion; asana (à¤†à¤¸à¤¨) - pose. The second variation of the lion pose.', 'This variation emphasizes adductor engagement and maintaining verticality through the torso while the hips are in adduction and external rotation. The spine is kept elongated, counteracting compression from the seated position.', 'A diagonal slash ascends from left to right. A solid bindu is placed at the base of the slash, representing the root.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/050_master_simhasana_ii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/050_simhasanaii.mp3', NULL, NULL, 2, '{"flow": 5, "long": 45, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '[]', false),
	('Viranchyasana II', '145', 'ViranchyÄsana II', 'Final: 388', 10, true, 304, 249, 'Assume Virasana with one leg. Take the other leg. Bring the other leg behind your neck. Hold this combination of poses. Perform the pose on the opposite side. This movement frees the shoulders.', '08_Advanced_Leg_behind_Head', NULL, NULL, 'Viranchiâ€™s Pose II', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Viranchyasana Two
This pose combines Virasana with leg-behind-head complexity.
Effects: Shoulder movements freer.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤µà¤¿à¤°à¤žà¥à¤šà¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"The Pose Dedicated to Viranchi (Brahma) II"', 'This variation emphasizes adductor engagement and hip abduction to maintain the integrity of the extended leg and the stability of the standing leg. Precise alignment of the spine from coccyx to crown is essential for balance and structural support.', 'A square frame with a diagonal slash from the upper-left to the lower-right. A solid bindu is positioned in the bottom-left corner of the square, touching both the frame and the slash.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/145_master_viranchyasana_ii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/145_viranchyasanaii.mp3', NULL, NULL, 8, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 30, "standard": 45}', '[]', false),
	('Ashtanga Namaskara', '228', 'Aá¹£á¹­Äá¹…ga NamaskÄra', NULL, 1, false, NULL, NULL, 'Begin from a plank or equestrian position. On an exhalation, lower the knees to the floor while keeping the toes tucked under. Keeping the elbows hugged tightly in toward the ribs, lower the chest and chin down to the floor between the hands. Ensure the chest touches the ground while the hips and abdomen remain lifted and angled toward the ceiling. Balance the body weight evenly across the eight points of contact: the palms, chin, chest, knees, and toes. Maintain smooth breathing and keep the core slightly engaged to support the lift of the midsection.', '11_Ayurvedic_Toning', 'Ensure the hips and abdomen remain lifted; only the eight specific points should touch the floor.', NULL, 'Eight Limbs Position', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Eight Limbs Position (Ashtanga Namaskara)
A yoga posture where the body rests on eight points of contact with the floor: both feet, both knees, both hands, the chest, and the chin or forehead. It is a foundational transition in Sun Salutations.
Effects: Strengthens the arms, chest, and core muscles, improves flexibility in the spine and neck, and serves as an excellent preparation for deeper backbending poses.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤…à¤·à¥à¤Ÿà¤¾à¤™à¥à¤— à¤¨à¤®à¤¸à¥à¤•à¤¾à¤°', '"Eight-Limbed Salutation"', 'Simultaneous placement of eight points on the ground creates a stable structural base. Adductor engagement and spinal extension counteract the force of gravity.', 'Within a square frame, two parallel horizontal lines represent the pectoral girdle. A downward-pointing isosceles triangle rests centrally beneath the lines, its apex near the bottom of the frame, symbolizing the grounding sternum.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/228_master_astanga_namaskara.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/228_ashtanganamaskara.mp3', NULL, NULL, 11, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '[]', false),
	('Vamadevasana II', '167', 'VÄmadevÄsana II', 'Final: 466', 15, true, 347, 289, 'Assume Bhekasana with one leg. Assume Padmasana with the other leg. Join the soles of the feet. This completes the pose.', '08_Advanced_Leg_behind_Head', NULL, NULL, 'Vamadevaâ€™s Pose II', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Vamadevasana Two
The technique involves one leg in Bhekasana and the other in Padmasana, then joining the soles.
Effects: Relieves leg pain and stiffness, improves digestion.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤µà¤¾à¤®à¤¦à¥‡à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Vamadeva''s Pose II"; Vamadeva is a name of Shiva; asana, posture.', 'This variation emphasizes lateral extension while maintaining a strong foundation. The core stabilizes as the leg extends, fostering balance and length through the spine.', 'An open circle at the base supports an off-center vertical line. A second line branches upward at 60 degrees from the circle''s edge on the opposite side, suggesting asymmetric extension and groundedness.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/167_master_vamadevasana_ii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/167_vamadevasanaii.mp3', NULL, NULL, 2, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 30, "standard": 45}', '[]', false),
	('Salamba Sirsasana III', '077', 'SÄlamba ÅšÄ«á¹›sÄsana III', 'Final: 194, 195 | Int: 193, 196, 197', 8, false, 192, 154, 'Place your palms on the blanket. Ensure your fingers point toward your feet. Tuck your toes. Lift your knees off the floor. Straighten your legs. This forms Dolphin Pose. Walk your feet toward your head. Your hips should align above your shoulders. Keep pressing firmly through your arms. Place the crown of your head on the blanket. Press down through your arms. Draw your shoulder blades away from your ears. Lift your legs up. Bring your legs perpendicular to the floor. Maintain a steady gaze. Breathe evenly in the pose.', '04_Inversions_Sirsasana_Sarvangasana', NULL, NULL, 'Supported Headstand III', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Salamba Sirsasana three or Headstand three
This posture is the supported headstand variation three.
Effects: Firmness and confidence in balance.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤¸à¤¾à¤²à¤®à¥à¤¬ à¤¶à¥€à¤°à¥à¤·à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Supported Headstand III": *salamba* (supported), *sirsa* (head), *asana* (posture).', 'This variation emphasizes precise spinal alignment and adductor engagement to maintain verticality and balance. The pose integrates the actions of grounding through the forearms and extending through the spine.', 'A vertical line represents the central axis of the body. Concentric arcs emanate from the base, suggesting stability and expansion. A solid bindu sits atop the vertical line, symbolizing focused awareness.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/077_master_salamba_sirsasana_iii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/077_salambasirsasanaiii.mp3', NULL, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 480, "short": 180, "standard": 300}', '[]', false),
	('Eka Pada Rajakapotasana III', '187', 'Eka PÄda RÄjakapotÄsana III', 'Final: 546', 30, true, 393, 326, 'Begin in Ardha Kapotasana, or Half Pigeon Pose. Fold the left leg in front. Extend the right leg back. Lengthen the spine and the hips. Inhale and lift the torso. Draw the shoulder blades down and in. Open your heart forward. Bend the right knee slowly and mindfully. Draw the right foot toward your head. Hold the right ankle with your right hand. Gently twist right. Inhale again and backbend the torso. Bring the chest out and shoulders back. Hold the foot. Twist the shoulders. Reach the left hand back if possible. Hold the foot with both hands if comfortable. Flex the quadriceps and glute muscles. Engage your shoulders and abdomen for support.', '09_Backbends', NULL, NULL, 'One-Legged King Pigeon Pose III', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Eka Pada Rajakapotasana three or King pigeon three
This pose involves one leg in Virasana style and the other leg back, catching the foot.
Effects: Rejuvenates spine, strengthens thighs, strengthens ankles.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤à¤• à¤ªà¤¾à¤¦ à¤°à¤¾à¤œà¤•à¤ªà¥‹à¤¤à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"One-Footed King Pigeon Pose, Variation III": eka (one), pada (foot/leg), raja (king), kapota (pigeon), asana (posture).', 'This advanced variation focuses on deep hip opening and spinal extension. The adductor magnus draws the femur inward, while latissimus dorsi assists in spinal arch.', 'Within a square frame, three lines intersect, forming an inverted ''Y''. The central vertical line represents spinal alignment. The two angled lines, bisecting the lower quadrants, symbolize the grounding leg and lifted leg. An equilateral triangle is positioned at the apex of the ''Y'', pointing downwards, representing the sacrum.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/187_master_eka_pada_rajakapotasana_iii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/187_ekapadarajakapotasanaiii.mp3', NULL, NULL, 9, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '[]', false),
	('Parsva Bakasana', '153', 'PÄrÅ›va BakÄsana', 'Final: 412 | Int: 411', 16, true, 318, 263, 'Begin in Chair Pose with hands in Anjali Mudra. Exhale and twist your torso to the left. Plant your hands flat on the floor shoulder-width apart. Engage your shoulder girdle. Bend your elbows like Chaturanga arms. Stack both knees on the shelf of the opposite upper arm near the armpit. Lean forward into your hands. Lift your feet from the floor. Extend your legs straight back if possible. Maintain a strong core engagement. Keep your gaze forward. Release slowly back to a squatting position. Come to Downward Facing Dog. Rest in Child''s Pose.', '08_Advanced_Leg_behind_Head', NULL, NULL, 'Side Crow Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Parsva Bakasana or Side crane
This pose is technique number one hundred fifty-three.
Effects: Intestines grow stronger, develops lateral abdominal muscles, strengthens arms.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '132', 'à¤ªà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤¬à¤•à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Side Crane Pose": à¤ªà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µ (pÄrÅ›va) = side, à¤¬à¤• (baka) = crane, à¤†à¤¸à¤¨ (Äsana) = pose.', 'Parsva Bakasana establishes a strong, twisted foundation through adductor engagement. The spine extends axially, counteracting the forward lean and rotational forces.', 'Three intersecting lines within a square frame. Two lines form an acute angle pointing downwards. A concentric arc intersects the apex of this angle, subtly echoing the pose''s bent form.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/153_master_parsva_bakasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/153_parsvabakasana.mp3', 132.00, NULL, 7, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '[]', false),
	('Bhairavasana', '139', 'BhairavÄsana', 'Final: 375', 16, true, 296, 242, 'Begin by sitting in Staff Pose (Dandasana). Bend your right knee. Turn the right knee slightly out to the side. Lift your right leg. Place the right leg behind your neck. Extend the left leg straight on the floor. Hold the pose. This is a supine hip and spine stretch.', '08_Advanced_Leg_behind_Head', NULL, NULL, 'Fierce Bhairava Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Bhairavasana
The name means Terrible aspect of Siva.
Effects: Supine hip and spine stretch.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤­à¥ˆà¤°à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Fierce Form" or "Terror Pose", from Bhairava (a fierce manifestation of Shiva) and Asana (posture).', 'This posture demands significant adductor engagement to maintain the leg''s elevated position while simultaneously requiring spinal stability and a deep hip hinge to achieve the final expression.', 'A square frame contains an offset vertical axis line. An open circle resides adjacent to this line within the frame, positioned towards the upper left quadrant, symbolizing imbalance and dynamic tension.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/139_master_bhairavasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/139_bhairavasana.mp3', NULL, NULL, 8, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 30, "standard": 45}', '[]', false),
	('Jalandhara Bandha', '219', 'JÄlandhara bandha', 'Final: 614', 2, false, NULL, NULL, 'Sit in a comfortable position such as the accomplished pose or the lotus pose. Keep the back erect and rigid. Lift the sternum and the front part of the rib cage toward the ceiling. Stretch the sides of the neck without creating tension. Move the shoulder blades deep into the body. Maintain a concave shape in the thoracic and cervical spine. Bend the head forward and downward from the back of the neck. Keep the neck and throat muscles soft and receptive. Rest the point and both sides of the jawbone evenly in the notch between the collarbones. Lift the top of the chest to meet the descending chin. Align the center of the head and the chin with the middle of the breastbone. Keep the navel and the perineum in a straight vertical line with the chin. Relax the temples and keep the eyes and ears passive. Soften the tongue and the internal throat. Ensure the ribs do not cave inward while the chin rests on the chest. Maintain an even pressure on both sides of the jaw. Relax the facial skin and the forehead completely. Lower the shoulders away from the ears. Keep the spinal column firm and tall throughout the practice.', '10_Restorative_Pranayama', NULL, NULL, 'Chin Lock', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Jalandhara Bandha
It is said to be the lion that kills the elephant named death.
Effects: exercises the diaphragm, through uddiyana bandha the great bird prana is forced to fly up through the sushumna nadi, the main channel for the flow of nervous energy, which is situated inside the spinal column (merudanda).', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤œà¤¾à¤²à¤¨à¥à¤§à¤°à¤¬à¤¨à¥à¤§', '"Jala" (net), "dhar" (holding), "bandha" (lock). The throat lock.', 'Approximation of the sternum to the jugular notch compresses the throat. Stabilizes blood pressure by regulating flow to the head, thus maintaining internal pressure.', 'Within a square frame, a central vertical hairline descends from the top edge. Three concentric semi-circular arcs, their open ends facing downwards, are stacked beneath it, representing the progressive engagement of the throat lock.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/219_master_jalandhara_bandha.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/219_JalandharaBandha.mp3', NULL, NULL, 10, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Ashwa Sanchalanasana', '227', 'AÅ›wa SaÃ±calanÄsana', NULL, 1, true, NULL, NULL, 'Begin in a standing forward bend (Uttanasana) with the palms on the floor beside the feet. On an inhalation, step one leg far back, resting the knee and the ball of the foot on the mat. Align the front knee at a 90-degree angle directly above the ankle, keeping the thigh parallel to the floor. Place the fingertips or palms on the floor on either side of the front foot, shoulder-width apart. Roll the shoulders back and down to open the chest and lengthen the spine. Gently lower the hips and pelvis toward the floor. Tilt the head slightly backward and direct the gaze forward or slightly upward. Hold the posture while taking slow, deep breaths, sinking the hips further with each exhalation. To release, inhale and step the back foot forward to return to Uttanasana. Repeat the sequence by stepping the opposite leg back.', '11_Ayurvedic_Toning', 'Ensure the front knee is directly above the ankle to protect the joint; use a blanket under the back knee for comfort if needed.', NULL, 'Equestrian Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Equestrian Position (Ashwa Sanchalanasana)
A foundational asymmetrical low lunge that stretches the hips and groin while grounding the body.
Effects: Stretches the hip flexors and psoas muscles, tones the abdominal organs, improves balance, and promotes mental focus and stability.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤…à¤¶à¥à¤µ à¤¸à¤‚à¤šà¤²à¤¨à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Equestrian Posture', 'Ashwa Sanchalanasana, a variation of the root pose, involves deep flexion of the hip joint in the forward leg, coupled with extension in the trailing leg; this requires the psoas major of the back leg to lengthen as the quadriceps of the front leg engage to stabilize the knee. Simultaneous engagement of the trapezius and serratus anterior facilitates opening the chest and lifting the frontal iliac spines, creating space in the abdomen.', 'The symbol consists of two parallel lines representing the grounded legs, and concentric arcs above them to signify the expanding energy of the torso and breath.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/227_master_aswa_sancalanasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/227_ashwasanchalanasana.mp3', NULL, NULL, 11, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '[]', false),
	('Dhyana', '218', 'DhyÄna', 'Final: 602', 1, false, NULL, NULL, 'DhyÄna means absorption. It is the art of self-study, reflection, keen observation, or the search for the Infinite within. It is the observation of the physical processes of the body, the study of mental states, and profound contemplation. It means looking inward to oneâ€™s innermost being. DhyÄna is the discovery of the Self.  When the powers of the intellect and the heart are harmoniously blended, this is dhyÄna. All creativity proceeds from it, and its good and beautiful results benefit mankind.  DhyÄna is like deep sleep, but with a difference. The serenity of deep sleep comes as a result of unconsciously forgetting oneâ€™s identity and individuality, whereas meditation brings serenity that is alert and conscious throughout. The sÄdhaka remains a witness (sÄká¹£Ä«) to all activities. Chronological and psychological time have no existence in deep sleep or in total absorption. In sleep, the body and mind recover from wear and tear and feel fresh upon waking. In meditation, the sÄdhaka experiences illumination.  DhyÄna is the full integration of the contemplator, the act of contemplation, and the object contemplated, becoming one. The distinction between the knower, the instrument of knowledge, and the object known vanishes. The sÄdhaka becomes vibrant, alert, and poised. He becomes free from hunger, thirst, sleep, and sex, as well as from desire, anger, greed, infatuation, pride, and envy. He is unassailable by the dualities of body and mind, or mind and Self. His vision reflects his true Self like a well-polished mirror. This is Ä€tma-darÅ›ana, the reflection of the Soul.  Jesus said that man does not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceeds out of the mouth of God. Pondering upon the meaning of life, man becomes convinced that within his soul dwells a force or light far greater than himself. Yet in his walk of life he is beset by many cares and doubts. Caught in the environment of artificial civilisation, he develops a false sense of values. His words and actions run counter to his thoughts. Bewildered by these contradictions, he realises that life is full of oppositesâ€”pain and pleasure, sorrow and joy, conflict and peace. Seeing these polarities, he strives to attain balance and to find a state of stability so that he may experience freedom from pain, sorrow, and conflict. In his search he discovers the three noble paths of knowledge (jÃ±Äna), work (karma), and worship (bhakti), which teach him that his inner light is the only guide leading to mastery over his own life. To reach this inner light, he turns to meditation or dhyÄna.  To have a clear notion of the true natures of man, the world, and God, the sÄdhaka should study the sacred books (Å›Ästras). Then he can distinguish the real from the unreal. Knowledge of these three truths (tattva-traya)â€”the soul (cit), the world (acit), and God (ÄªÅ›vara)â€”is essential for one who seeks liberation. Such knowledge gives insight into lifeâ€™s problems and their solutions and strengthens spiritual practice. Yet knowledge acquired by reading alone will not lead to liberation. It is through courage and unshakable faith in the teachings of the sacred books, and by putting them into practice until they become part of daily life, that the sÄdhaka gains freedom from the domination of the senses. Knowledge of the scriptures and sÄdhana are the two wings by which the sÄdhaka flies towards liberation.  Man is drawn between two paths. One drags him downwards toward the fulfilment of voluptuous desires and sense gratification, leading to bondage and destruction; the other guides him upwards toward purity and realisation of his inner Self. Desires fog the mind and veil the true Self. It is the mind alone that leads to bondage or to liberation. It is reason or intelligence that either controls the mind or allows itself to be dominated.  An untrained mind flies aimlessly in all directions. The practice of meditation brings it to a state of stability and then directs it to proceed from imperfect knowledge to perfection. The sÄdhakaâ€™s mind and intelligence work as an integrated team led by will-power. He finds harmony between his thoughts, speech, and actions. His stilled mind and intelligence burn like a lamp in a windless place, with simplicity, innocence, and illumination.  Man has great potentialities that lie dormant within him. His body and mind are like fallow land lying untilled and unsown. A wise farmer ploughs his land (ká¹£etra), provides it with water and fertiliser, plants the best seeds, carefully tends the crops, and ultimately reaps a good harvest. To the sÄdhaka, his body, mind, and intellect are the field he ploughs with energy and right action. He sows the finest seeds of knowledge, waters them with devotion, and tends them with unrelenting spiritual discipline to reap the harvest of harmony and peace. He then becomes the wise owner (ká¹£etrajÃ±a) of his field, and his body becomes a sacred place. The germination of good thoughts (savicÄra), planted by sound logic (savitarka), brings clarity to the mind and wisdom to the intellect (sasmita). He becomes an abode of joy (Äda), as his whole being is filled with the Lord.  The journey to the moon and outer space demanded years of rigorous training and discipline, deep study, research, and preparation. The inward journey of man to reach his inner Self demands the same relentless effort. Years of discipline and long, uninterrupted practice of the moral and ethical principles of yama and niyama, training of the body through Äsana and prÄá¹‡ÄyÄma, restraint of the senses through pratyÄhÄra and dhÄraá¹‡Ä, ensure the growth of the mind and inner awarenessâ€”dhyÄna and samÄdhi.  DhÄraá¹‡Ä (derived from the root dhr, meaning â€œto holdâ€ or concentration) is like a lamp that is covered and does not light up the area outside. When the cover is removed, the lamp illuminates the whole area. This is dhyÄnaâ€”the expansion of consciousness. The sÄdhaka acquires a unified mind and maintains a dynamic, unfading awareness in its pristine purity. Like oil in seeds and fragrance in flowers, the soul permeates the whole body.  The lotus is symbolic of meditation. It symbolises purity. Its quiet beauty has given it a prime place in Indian religious thought. It is connected with most Hindu deities and their seats in the cakras. The stage of meditation is like a lotus bud hiding its inner beauty while awaiting transformation into a fully blossomed lotus. As the bud opens to reveal its splendour, so too the sÄdhakaâ€™s inner light is transformed and transfigured by meditation. He becomes an enlightened soul (siddha) and an inspired sage. He lives in the eternal nowâ€”the presentâ€”without yesterdays or tomorrows.  This state of the sÄdhaka is one of passivity known as manolaya (manas meaning mind, and laya meaning absorption or merging). He has fully marshalled his intelligence (prajÃ±Ä) and energy (prÄá¹‡a) to prevent the intrusion of external thoughts. His state is full of dynamic alertness. When both internal and external thoughts are stilled and silenced, there is no waste of physical, mental, or intellectual energy.  DhyÄna is a subjective experience of an objective state. It is difficult to describe in words, for words are inadequate. The delight experienced at the first bite of a delicious mango is indescribable; so it is with meditation. In meditation there is no seeking or searching, for the soul and the goal have become one. The nectar of infinity must be tasted; the abundant grace of the Lord within must be experienced. Then the individual soul (jÄ«vÄtman) becomes one with the Universal Soul (ParamÄtman).  The sÄdhaka experiences the fullness sung by the Upaniá¹£ads:  That is full; this is full. From fullness comes fullness. Even when fullness is taken from fullness, fullness remains.', '10_Restorative_Pranayama', NULL, NULL, 'Meditation', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Dhyana
Dhyana means absorption and is the act of self-study, reflection, keen observation, or the search for the Infinite within.
Effects: full integration of the contemplator, the act of contemplation, and the object contemplated upon becoming one, distinction between the knower, the instrument of knowledge and the object known vanishes, sadhaka becomes vibrant, alert and poised, sadhaka becomes free from hunger, thirst, sleep and sex as well as from desire, anger, greed, infatuation, pride and envy, sadhaka becomes unassailable by the dualities of body and mind or mind and self, sadhaka''s vision reflects his true self like a well-polished mirror, brings the mind to a state of stability and directs it to proceed from imperfect knowledge to perfection, sadhaka experiences illumination.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤§à¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¨', 'From Sanskrit ''dhyai'' meaning ''to think of''. Rooted in focused contemplation.', 'Dhyana necessitates spinal extension, achieved via abdominal engagement and adductor contraction; foundationally, it cultivates the energetic ''mulabandha''.', 'Within a square frame, a diagonal slash ascends from the bottom left. An equilateral triangle, its apex pointing downwards, is positioned directly above the slash, bisected by the top right corner of the frame.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/218_master_dhyana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/218_dhyana.mp3', NULL, NULL, 10, '{"flow": 5, "long": 600, "short": 180, "standard": 300}', '[]', false),
	('Goraksasana', '054', 'Goraá¸³sÄsana', 'Final: 117', 10, false, 142, 111, 'Sit on the floor in Padmasana. Stretch your arms forward and place them on the floor. Raise your trunk. Lift your hips off the floor. Keep your trunk straight. Stand up with your knees still bent. Stretch your thighs. Gradually lift your hands off the floor one by one. Maintain the balance of your spine. Join your hands in a prayer position in front of your chest.', '02_Seated_and_Lotus_Variations', NULL, NULL, 'Gorakshaâ€™s Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Goraksasana
Goraksa means a cowherd.
Effects: Achieves sense of balance, coccyx gets elasticity, develops balance, provides coccyx elasticity.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤—à¥‹à¤°à¤•à¥à¤·à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Cowherd''s Pose"; from ''goraksha'' (cowherd, protector of cows) and ''asana'' (pose).', 'Heels pressed into the perineum create a stable base. Opposing forces of grounding and spinal extension lengthen the core, promoting stability and awareness.', 'An equilateral triangle rests on its apex. Three lines bisect the triangle: one vertical, one angled right, and one angled left, all intersecting at the triangle''s centroid.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/054_master_goraksasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/054_goraksasana.mp3', NULL, NULL, 2, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Bharadvajasana I', '112', 'BharadvÄjÄsana I', 'Final: 297, 298', 1, true, 251, 204, 'Sit on the floor with your legs extended straight in front of you, spine tall, and hands by your hips.
Lean slightly to your right side and bend both knees, swinging your feet around to the left side so they rest on the floor outside your left hip.
Bring your right ankle into the arch of your left foot, with the right buttock and left hip resting on the floor (or on a blanket if necessary).
Inhale to lengthen your spine, lifting through the sternum. On an exhale, twist your torso to the right.
Place your right hand behind you on the floor for support.
Place your left hand on the outside of your right knee or thigh.
Gaze and Breath: Keep the shoulders relaxed away from the ears and gently look over your right shoulder.
Reach your right arm behind your back to catch the upper left arm.
Hold and Release: Maintain the pose for 30â€“60 seconds while breathing smoothly. Release with an exhalation, return to Dandasana, and repeat on the other side', '06_Twists', NULL, 'I', 'Bharadvajaâ€™s Twist I', '20/2/2026 3:57pm', 'Bharadvajasana I
