Effects: Strengthens neck, shoulders, abdomen, and spine.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '105', 'à¤Šà¤°à¥à¤§à¥à¤µà¤¦à¤£à¥à¤¡à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Upward Staff Pose"; à¤Šà¤°à¥à¤§à¥à¤µ (Å«rdhva) = upward, raised; à¤¦à¤£à¥à¤¡ (daá¹‡á¸a) = staff, stick; à¤†à¤¸à¤¨ (Äsana) = pose.', 'Urdhva Dandasana establishes the foundation for advanced backbends by emphasizing quadriceps engagement and spinal extension. The posture builds balanced strength through reciprocal flexion and extension vectors.', 'A diagonal slash bisects an open circle. The slash represents the dynamic line of force from the feet to the spine; the circle embodies the integrated core.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/075_master_urdhva_dandasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/075_urdhvadandasana.mp3', 105.00, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 90, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Parsvottanasana', '012', 'PÄrÅ›vÅttÄnÄsana', 'Final: 26, 27, 28 | Int: 24, 25', 6, true, NULL, NULL, 'Stand in Tadasana. Join your palms in Namaste behind your back. Jump your legs three to three and a half feet apart. Turn your body to the right. Exhale and bend your torso forward. Rest your head on your right knee. Hold the posture for twenty to thirty seconds.', '01_Standing_and_Basic', '', 'II,III,I', 'Intense Side Stretch Pose', '16/2/2026 2:37pm', 'Parsvottanasana or Intense Side Stretch Pose
This pose involves a wide stance with the upper body folded over the front leg.
Effects: Elasticizes hip joints and spine, tones abdominal organs.', true, NULL, '{"asana_id": "233", "stage_id": null}', '7', '40', 'à¤ªà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µà¥‹à¤¤à¥à¤¤à¤¾à¤¨à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Intense Side Stretch Pose": PÄrÅ›va (side), UttÄna (extended, stretched out), Ä€sana (pose).', 'Parsvottanasana aligns the sagittal plane with a stable base, promoting spinal extension and hamstring flexibility through adductor engagement. The pose emphasizes a precise relationship between the legs, pelvis, and torso, maintaining an anterior pelvic tilt to deepen the stretch.', 'A concentric arc extends downward from a vertical hairline, and a smaller concentric arc mirrors the first from below, both on the left side. The right side has a vertical hairline only.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/012_master_parsvottanasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/012_parsvottanasana.mp3', 40.00, NULL, 1, '{"flow": 5, "long": 90, "short": 60, "standard": 75}', '15', false),
	('Mula Bandha', '220', 'MÅ«la Bandha', 'Final: 615', 3, false, NULL, NULL, 'Sit in a stable meditative asana with the spinal column firm and tall. Perform the chin lock (Jalandhara Bandha) by lowering the head toward the trunk. Place the back of the wrists on the knees and keep the eyes and ears passive. Contract the muscles of the principal region between the anus and the genitals. Lift these perineal muscles vertically toward the navel. Press the lower anterior abdomen located below the navel backwards toward the spine. Pull this same lower abdominal area upwards toward the spine. Move the anal sphincter muscles toward the center of the body in the manner of asvini mudra. Draw only the area between the anus and the navel back toward the spinal column. Lift this specific region up toward the diaphragm. Maintain this contraction during the period of internal breath retention after inhalation. Keep the upper abdominal region above the navel soft and unconstricted. Ensure the chest remains lifted and the shoulders stay relaxed. Practice this root lock (Mula Bandha) while performing the camel pose (Ustrasana). Integrate the contraction while staying in the headstand (Sirsasana). Apply the lock during the practice of the shoulder stand (Sarvangasana). Use the muscular lift while in the upward-facing bow pose (Urdhva Dhanurasana). Maintain the internal grip during the seated forward bend (Paschimottanasana). Hold the contraction firmly without straining the facial muscles. Release the pelvic lift gradually before the final exhalation. Lower the right hand and raise the head to a neutral position. Relax the entire body in the corpse pose (Savasana).', '10_Restorative_Pranayama', NULL, NULL, 'Root Lock', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Mula Bandha
The yogi attempts to reach the true source (mula) of all creation.
Effects: The lift of the diaphragm gently massages the muscles of the heart thereby toning them, it tones the abdominal organs, increases the gastric fire, eliminates toxins in the digestive tract, the practitioner acquires moral and spiritual power which will shine forth like the sun.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤®à¥‚à¤²à¤¬à¤¨à¥à¤§à¤¶à¥à¤¸à¤¨', 'MÅ«la Bandha: Root Lock. ''MÅ«la'' = root, base, origin. ''Bandha'' = lock, bond, contract.', 'Mula Bandha involves the contraction of the pelvic floor muscles, specifically the perineum. This action draws energy upwards, stabilizing the base of the spine and activating core support.', 'Within a square frame, two parallel vertical lines represent the grounding legs. Three concentric semi-circular arcs, their open ends facing upwards and bisected by the lines, suggest the controlled contraction and energy containment.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/220_master_mula_bandha.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/220_MulaBandha.mp3', NULL, NULL, 10, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Ardha Padmasana', '230', 'Ardha PadmÄsana', 'Final: 7, 8', 1, true, NULL, NULL, 'Start in Staff Pose (Dandasana) sitting with the legs straight and the spine long. Bend the left knee fully and bring the foot toward the body. Gently guide the foot by externally rotating the hip so the outer edge of the foot rests on the opposite thigh, nestling the heel into the hip crease near the navel. Tuck the right foot under the left thigh, allowing the left knee to descend toward the floor. Maintain a tall spine and relaxed shoulders while pulling the navel gently inward. Use a cushion under the hips if necessary to ensure the lower back does not round.', NULL, NULL, NULL, 'Lotus Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Half Lotus (Ardha Padmasana) is a yoga and meditation pose where one foot rests on the opposite thigh, while the other leg stays tucked underneath, requiring significant hip external rotation and flexibility, with benefits like calming the mind, improving circulation, and strengthening the back, but it''s crucial to avoid knee pain by using props like cushions or blocks and practicing hip openers first. Proper execution involves flexing the knee, externally rotating the hip, bringing the heel towards the pelvis, and keeping the spine straight, using support to prevent strain.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤…à¤°à¥à¤§ à¤ªà¤¦à¥à¤®à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Half Lotus Pose": ardha (à¤…à¤°à¥à¤§) = "half," padma (à¤ªà¤¦à¥à¤®) = "lotus," asana (à¤†à¤¸à¤¨) = "seat/pose."', 'Ardha Padmasana initiates hip opening and spinal alignment. The pose structurally facilitates internal rotation of one hip and external rotation of the other while encouraging vertical lift through the torso.', 'Within a square frame, a vertical hairline is offset to the right. A crescent shape, its curve facing left, is positioned on the left side of the frame, suggesting the half-opening and the grounded hip.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/230_master_ardha_padmasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/230_ArdhaPadmasana.mp3', NULL, NULL, 2, '{"flow": 5, "long": 600, "short": 180, "standard": 300}', '[]', false),
	('Vrschikasana I', '182', 'á¹¾rÅ›chikÄsana I', 'Final: 536, 537', 32, false, 386, 319, 'Press your inner wrists down. Lift your shoulders. Press your wrists down. Lift your collar bones up. Lift the space between your collar bones up. Slide your sternum bone and chin towards the wall. As you slide your sternum towards the wall, lift the back of your pelvis upwards. Move your tailbone towards your inner groins. Move your inner groins towards your tail bone. Lift your legs away from your spine. Kick both feet up to the wall into Pincha Mayurasana. Bend both knees. Bring your heels towards your head.', '09_Backbends', NULL, NULL, 'Scorpion Pose I', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Vrschikasana I or Forearm scorpion
