	('Niralamba Sarvangasana II', '090', 'NirÄlamba SarvÄngÄsana II', 'Final: 237', 4, false, 215, 174, 'Lie down on your back facing the ceiling. Outstretch your legs parallel to each other. Outstretch your arms parallel to your body beside you. Transition from Sarvangasana into the unsupported pose. Release your arms from supporting your back. Engage your abdominal strength to lift your legs and arms skyward. Rest your body weight solely on your shoulders. Keep your legs elevated and straight. Keep your feet and toes together. Point your toes up towards the ceiling. Broaden and engage your shoulders. Press your neck against the ground in a forward bend. Keep your hips squared and lifted. Keep your palms on or by the side of your knees.', '04_Inversions_Sirsasana_Sarvangasana', NULL, NULL, 'Unsupported Shoulderstand II', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Niralamba Sarvangasana II or Unsupported shoulderstand II.
This pose is the unsupported version of the second shoulderstand.
Effects: Hardest Sarvangasana, extends vertebrae more than others, hardest shoulderstand, maximum vertebral extension.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 'à¤¨à¤¿à¤°à¤¾à¤²à¤®à¥à¤¬ à¤¸à¤°à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤™à¥à¤—à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Unsupported Shoulder Stand II: ''Nir'' (without), ''alamba'' (support), ''sarva'' (all), ''anga'' (limb), ''asana'' (pose).', 'In Niralamba Sarvangasana II, the absence of manual support demands precise engagement of core musculature and refined spinal alignment for stability. The pose necessitates a balanced distribution of weight across the shoulder girdle while maintaining a perpendicular relationship between the torso and the ground.', 'A hexagon frame houses three intersecting lines. One line bisects the hexagon vertically. The remaining two lines diagonally intersect the central line equidistant from the top and bottom vertices, forming an ''X'' shape within the hexagon. This represents balanced distribution in the unsupported inversion.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/090_master_niralamba_sarvangasana_ii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/090_niralambasarvangasanaii.mp3', 109.00, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 45, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Parsva Pindasana in Sarvangasana', '104', 'PÄrÅ›va Piá¹‡dÄsana in SarvÄngÄsana', 'Final: 270, 271', 8, true, 234, 191, 'Begin in Pindasana. Maintain a strong Sarvangasana foundation. Slowly turn the hips sideways. Lower both knees towards the floor. Hold the pose and breathe evenly. Return to Pindasana.', '04_Inversions_Sirsasana_Sarvangasana', NULL, NULL, 'Side Embryo Pose in Shoulderstand', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Parsva Pindasana in Sarvangasana or Side embryo in shoulderstand
This pose is a side embryo variation performed while in a shoulderstand position.
Effects: Relieves chronic constipation, relieves stomach griping.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '115', 'à¤ªà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µà¤ªà¤¿à¤£à¥à¤¡à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Side Embryo Pose in Shoulderstand":  *parsva* (side), *pinda* (embryo/lump), *asana* (posture), *sarvanga* (entire body), *asana* (posture)', 'The pose emphasizes lateral flexion and compression of the spine, engaging the obliques and deep spinal muscles.  Adductor action is crucial for maintaining the folded leg position, creating a compact, stable form.', 'A triangular frame with its apex pointing downwards contains three intersecting lines. A vertical line bisects the triangle from top to bottom.  Two lines cross at the vertical line equidistant from the triangle''s apex and base, forming an ''X'' shape. A solid bindu is centered at the intersection point.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/104_master_parsva_pindasana_in_sarvangasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/104_parsvapindasanainsarvangasana.mp3', 115.00, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '105', false),
	('Parsva Urdhva Padmasana in Sarvangasana', '101', 'PÄrÅ›va Åªrdhva PadmÄsana in SarvÄngÄsana', 'Final: 262, 263, 264, 265', 7, true, 231, 188, 'Begin the practice in Shoulderstand Pose. Cross the legs into Lotus Pose. Stretch the crossed legs vertically up to enter Upward Lotus Pose. Slowly lower the knees down while moving the hips. Twist the hips and spine laterally towards the left side. Support the left buttocks with the left hand. Come back to the center by lifting the hips higher. Drop the knees and hips down towards the floor. Take the hips and spine in a lateral side bend and stretch towards the right side. Support the right buttocks with the right hand. Return to the center. Release the legs and stretch them to return to Shoulderstand Pose. Continue into an arched-back variation. Lower the feet toward the floor above the head. Press the upper arms down into the mat. Broaden the collarbones and roll the shoulders underneath the back. Clasp the hands behind the back. Press the pinky fingers into the mat. Press down firmly through the heels. Draw the thighs toward one another. Reach the backs of the thighs toward the knees to lengthen the spine. Release the hands slowly. Lower the body one vertebra at a time back to the mat.', '04_Inversions_Sirsasana_Sarvangasana', NULL, NULL, 'Side Upward Lotus Pose in Shoulderstand', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Parsva Urdhva Padmasana in Sarvangasana
Parsva means flank, and this is the lateral-twist variation of Urdhva Padmasana in Sarvangasana (Images two-hundred-sixty-twoâ€“two-hundred-sixty-five).
Effects: No benefits listed.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '115', 'à¤ªà¤¾à¤°à¥à¤¶à¥à¤µà¥‹à¤°à¥à¤§à¥à¤µà¤ªà¤¦à¥à¤®à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Lateral Elevated Lotus Pose in Shoulder Stand":  parsva (side, flank), urdhva (elevated, upward), padma (lotus), asana (pose), sarvanga (entire body), asana (pose).', 'Lateral spinal flexion is achieved in the inverted position. The adductors draw the legs towards the ears, maintaining the lotus bond.  Scapulae stabilized for spinal extension.', 'A rectangular frame contains an offset vertical axis line. A solid bindu is positioned laterally, away from the vertical axis, to visually represent spinal rotation and compression with focused, grounded energy.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/101_master_parsva_urdhva_padmasana_in_sarvangasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/101_parsvaurdhvapadmasanainsarvangasana.mp3', 115.00, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '[]', false),
	('Paripurna Navasana', '034', 'ParipÅ«á¹›na NÄvÄsana', 'Final: 78 | Int: 77 Intermediate:', 2, false, NULL, NULL, 'Sit on the floor. Stretch the legs straight in front. Exhale completely. Recline the trunk slightly backward. Simultaneously raise the legs from the floor. Keep the legs straight and stiff. Balance the body on the buttocks. Maintain an angle of sixty to sixty-five degrees between the trunk and legs. Remove the hands from the floor. Stretch the arms forward near the thighs. Hold the pose for thirty seconds.', '02_Seated_and_Lotus_Variations', '', NULL, 'Boat Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Paripurna Navasana or Complete Boat Pose
The posture here resembles that of a boat with oars.
Effects: Gives relief to persons who feel a bloating sensation in the abdomen due to gas, gives relief to those suffering from gastric complaints, reduces fat around the waistline, tones the kidneys.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '58', 'à¤ªà¤°à¤¿à¤ªà¥‚à¤°à¥à¤£ à¤¨à¤¾à¤µà¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Paripurna (complete), Nava (boat), Asana (pose).', 'The pose requires sustained adductor engagement for leg integrity and reciprocal spinal extension to counteract pelvic flexion. The posterior pelvic tilt serves as the foundation for hamstring origin anchoring.', 'Three intersecting lines form a central hexagonal vertex. The lines represent the core, legs, and spine, converging in balanced opposition.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/034_master_paripurna_navasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/034_paripurnanavasana.mp3', 58.00, NULL, 5, '{"flow": 5, "long": 90, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '111', false),
	('Supta Padangusthasana', '108', 'Supta PÄdÄngá»¥á¹£tÄsana', 'Final: 285, 286, 287 | Int: 284', 13, true, 244, 197, 'Lie down on your back. Extend both legs straight out. Inhale and bend your right knee toward your chest. Grip your right big toe with your right hand. Place your left hand on your left thigh to anchor it. Straighten your right leg toward the ceiling. Keep your left leg pressed firmly into the floor. On an exhalation, pull your chin toward your right knee. Inhale and return your head to the floor. Open your right leg out to the side toward the floor. Keep your left buttock grounded. Avoid lifting your left hip off the floor. Hold the posture. Release the big toe. Draw your right knee back to your chest. Straighten your right leg onto the floor. Repeat on the left side.', '05_Abdominal_and_Supine', NULL, 'I', 'Reclining Hand-to-Big-Toe Pose', '22/2/2026 11:17am', 'Supta Padangusthasana or Reclining big toe
This is the name of the pose.
Effects: Benefits sciatica and leg paralysis, removes hip stiffness.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '88', 'à¤¸à¥à¤ªà¥à¤¤à¤ªà¤¾à¤¦à¤¾à¤™à¥à¤—à¥à¤·à¥à¤ à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Reclining Big Toe Pose": supta (à¤¸à¥à¤ªà¥à¤¤) = reclining, pada (à¤ªà¤¾à¤¦) = foot, angusta (à¤…à¤™à¥à¤—à¥à¤·à¥à¤ ) = big toe, asana (à¤†à¤¸à¤¨) = pose.', 'The posture emphasizes the sequential engagement of the leg muscles, from the plantar fascia to the hip rotators, to create length in the hamstrings. Maintaining a neutral spine while leveraging adductor action is key.', 'A diagonal slash ascends from the bottom left, bisecting an equilateral triangle, apex down. The triangle represents the grounded pelvis; the slash, the extended leg.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/108_master_supta_padangustasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/108_suptapadangusthasana.mp3', 88.00, NULL, 5, '{"flow": 5, "long": 180, "short": 60, "standard": 120}', '117, 118, 119', false),
	('Marichyasana III', '114', 'MarÄ«chyÄsana III', 'Final: 303, 304 | Int: 301, 302', 10, true, NULL, NULL, 'Bend one knee up. Keep the other leg straight. Twist your trunk ninety degrees. Bend the left elbow in front of the right knee, forearm vertical. Take the right arm back. Press the left arm and right knee against each other to bring the left side of the trunk forwards.
Press the right fingertips down to turn the right side back.
Move the trunk closer to the right leg and place the back of the left armpit over the right knee. Turn the hops more. Move the left hip towards the bent leg and the right hip away from it. Stretch the left arm down and turn it in, with the palm facing back.
Bend the arm back round the right shin. Take the right arm behind the back; bend the elbow and clasp the left hand. Make the entwined side of the back concave.
Grip the hands well to increase the turn of the trunk. (Moving the hands away from the back intensifies the pose).
Turn the head to gaze over the right shoulder.
Release and turn to the front.
Repeat on the other side.', '06_Twists', NULL, NULL, 'Marichiâ€™s Pose III', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Marichyasana three or Sitting lateral twist.
This is a sitting lateral twist performed with one knee bent up and the other leg straight.
Effects: Splitting backaches and lumbago disappear, liver and spleen toned, cures splitting backaches, tones liver and spleen.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '73', 'à¤®à¤°à¥€à¤šà¥à¤¯à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Dedicated to the sage Marichi (light ray); Asana (posture). Third variation.', 'Emphasizes deep spinal twist, abdominal compression, and the grounding action of the ischial tuberosity. The posture integrates adductor engagement to stabilize the root.', 'An equilateral triangle, apex down, symbolizes grounding. A single vertical hairline ascends from the apex, bisecting the triangle and extending slightly beyond its top edge, representing spinal extension and axial rotation. A solid bindu is positioned on the hairline, within the triangle, near the base, indicating the navel point and abdominal compression.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/114_master_marichyasana_iii.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/114_marichyasanaiii.mp3', 73.00, NULL, 6, '{"flow": 5, "long": 90, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '127', false),
	('Ardha Matsyendrasana I', '116', 'Ardha MatsyendrÄsana I', 'Final: 311, 312 | Int: 307, 308, 309, 310, 313, 314, 315, 316', 8, true, NULL, NULL, 'Sit with your legs stretched out in front of you. Bend your right leg at the knee and turn it back. Lift your buttocks off the floor and place your right foot under them, keeping the foot horizontal so it acts as a cushion for you to sit on. Your right outer buttock should rest on the heel and the inner part on the sole. Now, bend your left leg at the knee and place the shin by the outer side of the right leg, so the left outer ankle is close to the outer side of the right thigh. Ensure your left foot and right knee are pointing forward. Keep your hands by your sides, maintain your balance, and take a few breaths.

If you feel your body tilting, ensure your buttocks are properly placed on the foot to create a solid base. If the pelvis feels heavy, the perpendicular leg may tilt at an incorrect angle, so take a moment to adjust. Exhale and revolve your trunk ninety degrees to the left. Place your left hand four to six inches behind your left buttock. Turn your spine so that your chest, stomach, and pelvis all turn to the left, moving beyond your perpendicular left thigh.

Bend your right arm at the elbow and bring it beyond the outer edge of your left thigh. Get the right armpit and the right side of your trunk close to the left knee and thigh, then encircle the left leg with your right arm. Take a breath. On your next exhale, lift your left hand off the floor, extend it from the shoulder while keeping your balance, and swing the arm back to place your hand on your right hip. Catch the fingers of your right hand with your left hand. As you continue to revolve, gradually clasp further to hold the palm and the wrist.

Turn your head toward your left shoulder and look to the left. Stay in this final position for twenty to thirty seconds. Your breathing might speed up at first, but let it return to normal. Remember that you need a firm grip, a broad chest, and a lifted waist to maintain balance. Release your hands, bring your trunk forward, and straighten your legs one at a time. Now perform the pose on the other side by sitting on your left foot and reversing all the movements. Stay for the same amount of time and then return to sitting with your legs extended.

If you find it difficult to sit on your foot, you can place your heel next to your buttock and use a thick folded blanket under your seat for height so the heel stays on the floor. If you cannot reach your hands behind your back, place your perpendicular leg near the opposite knee to avoid compressing the abdomen. Instead of reaching back, you can stretch your arm and hold your big toe, while the other arm wraps around your waist. You can also practice this against a wall for support. Sit with your leg along the wall, perform the leg positions, and press your palms against the wall to help your trunk rise and twist. This posture effectively massages the lower abdominal organs and strengthens the lower part of the back.', '06_Twists', '', NULL, 'Half Lord of the Fishes Pose I', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Matsya means fish, Indra is Lord. An interesting anecdote is connected with this asana. In Hatha yoga, Matsyendra is mentioned as one of the founders of Hatha Vidya. Lord Siva was once expounding Yoga Vidya to Parvati by the side of the river, where a fish was intently listening to the discourse. Lord Siva sprinkled some water on the fish and it became Matsyendra, Lord of the fishes.

The asana described here is half Matsyendrasana. For Paripurna or full Matsyendrasana refer to the relevant pose.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '74', 'à¤…à¤°à¥à¤§à¤®à¤¤à¥à¤¸à¥à¤¯à¥‡à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', '"Half Lord of the Fishes Pose I":  ardha (à¤…à¤°à¥à¤§) = half; matsya (à¤®à¤¤à¥à¤¸à¥à¤¯) = fish; indra (à¤‡à¤¨à¥à¤¦à¥à¤°) = lord; asana (à¤†à¤¸à¤¨) = pose.', 'This asana''s structural blueprint involves a twisting action around the spine, achieved through adductor engagement and controlled spinal elongation. Grounding through the sit bones anchors the pose.', 'A vertical hairline, slightly offset from the center, represents the spinal axis.  An open circle is positioned along the line, indicating the point of maximum spinal twist.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/116_master_ardha_matsyendrasana_i.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/116_ardhamatsyendrasanai.mp3', 74.00, NULL, 6, '{"long": 90, "short": 40, "standard": 55}', '128', false),
	('Pasasana', '119', 'PÄÅ›Äna', 'Final: 328, 329 | Int: 323, 324, 325, 326, 327', 15, true, 267, 217, 'Bend your knees and squat. Tone your legs. Stretch your spine long. Twist your torso. Place your outer right armpit to your outer left knee. Eliminate the gap between your shoulder and knee. Bring your arm around both thighs. Clasp your hands behind your back. Continually push your right heel down into the floor. Stretch your spine up. Take your arm bones back. Twist more.', '06_Twists', NULL, NULL, 'Noose Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Pasasana or Noose pose
The technique involves squatting, twisting the trunk, wrapping the arm around both thighs, and clasping the hands.
Effects: Recommended for persons suffering from diabetes, strengthens ankles, reduces abdominal fat, recommended for diabetes.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '76', 'à¤ªà¤¾à¤¶à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Noose Pose', 'Pasasana requires deep flexion of the knees and hips, demanding considerable ankle dorsiflexion and external rotation of the thighs; simultaneously, the pose necessitates spinal extension achieved by engaging the erector spinae and lifting the frontal iliac spines to prevent excessive rounding of the back. Furthermore, the binding action promotes scapular protraction and facilitates a stretch across the upper back muscles, while requiring significant shoulder internal rotation to clasp the hands behind.', 'The symbol for Pasasana features a stylized human figure within a square frame, illustrating the deep squat and spinal twist characteristic of the pose; the figure is slightly offset from the vertical axis of the square to emphasize the asymmetrical nature of the bind and the spinal rotation involved.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/119_master_pasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/119_pasasana.mp3', 76.00, NULL, 6, '{"flow": 5, "long": 60, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '131', false),
	('Parsvaikapada Sarvangasana', '096', 'PÄrÅ›vaika PÄda SarvÄngÄsana', 'Final: 251', 6, true, 225, 182, 'Begin in Shoulderstand Pose. Maintain the vertical extension of the body. Keep one leg extended upwards. Lower the other leg sideways toward the floor. Keep the lowered leg in line with the trunk. Keep the shoulders engaged. Push the tailbone upwards. Gaze toward the foot that is in the air. Return to Shoulderstand. Repeat the process on the opposite side.', '04_Inversions_Sirsasana_Sarvangasana', NULL, NULL, 'Side One-Legged Shoulderstand', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Parsvaika Pada Sarvangasana or Side one-leg shoulderstand
The technique involves lowering one leg sideways to the floor in line with the trunk.
Effects: Relieves constipation, tones kidneys.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '111', 'à¤¸à¤°à¥à¤µà¤¾à¤™à¥à¤—à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨', 'Parsvaikapada Sarvangasana (Side One-Legged Shoulder Stand)', 'In Parsvaikapada Sarvangasana, unilateral hip abduction occurs with the leg moving away from the midline, while the sacrum stabilizes against the support. The cervical vertebrae experience increased flexion, countered by engaging the trapezius to protect the neck.', 'The symbol features two parallel lines, representing the spine''s alignment, intersected by a hexagonal vertex, which symbolizes the six energetic centers (chakras) engaged during the asana.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/096_master_parsvaika_pada_sarvangasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/096_parsvaikapadasarvangasana.mp3', 111.00, NULL, 4, '{"flow": 5, "long": 120, "short": 30, "standard": 60}', '96, 172', false),
	('Dhanurasana', '027', 'DhanurÄsana', 'Final: 63', 4, false, 101, 75, 'Lie full length on the floor on the stomach. Face downwards. Exhale. Bend the knees. Stretch the arms back. Hold the left ankle with the left hand. Hold the right ankle with the right hand. Take two breaths. Exhale completely. Pull the legs up. Raise the knees above the floor. Simultaneously lift the chest off the floor. Lift up the head. Pull the head as far back as possible. Do not rest the ribs on the floor. Do not rest the pelvic bones on the floor. Only the abdomen bears the body''s weight.', '01_Standing_and_Basic', NULL, NULL, 'Bow Pose', '14/2/2026 4:12pm', 'Dhanurasana or Bow Pose
The arms and hands act like a bow-string to tauten the body like a bent bow.
Effects: Stretches the spine backward, restores spinal elasticity preventing rigidity in elderly, tones abdominal organs, provides non-surgical relief for slipped discs.', true, NULL, NULL, NULL, '94', 'à¤§à¤¨à¥à¤°à¤¾à¤¸à¤¨à¥‹à¤ªà¤¾à¤§à¤¿à¤•à¤®à¥', '"Bow Pose": dhanu (bow), asana (seat/pose)', 'Dhanurasana emphasizes backbend integrity through simultaneous spinal extension and engagement of the posterior chain. The adduction of the legs contributes to the stabilization of the sacrum, facilitating deeper opening.', 'A central vertical line represents the spine. Two intersecting lines extend outwards from the top of the vertical line, mimicking the arms reaching back. An open circle at the base of the vertical line symbolizes the grounded core.', true, '/storage/v1/object/public/yoga-cards/027_master_dhanurasana.webp', '/storage/v1/object/public/audio-assets/027_dhanurasana.mp3', 94.00, NULL, 9, '{"flow": 5, "long": 45, "short": 15, "standard": 30}', '136', false),
